    <section class="  shadow-lg rounded-lg p-6 mb-8">
      <h2 id="how-to-execute" class="text-3xl font-semibold  text-pink-400 mb-4">How to Execute the Perfect Lob Shot</h2>
      <p class="text-lg mb-6">
        Executing a perfect lob shot requires not only technical skill but also a keen sense of timing. Here's a breakdown of how to properly execute the lob shot:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-8 text-lg mb-6">
        <li><strong>Positioning:</strong> Start with a balanced stance, keeping your feet shoulder-width apart. Stand slightly behind the non-volley zone line if you're in the forecourt and be ready to make a quick movement toward the ball.</li>
        <li><strong>Grip:</strong> Use the continental grip for flexibility, allowing you to transition between different shots easily. This grip will give you control over the ball as you aim for precision in your lob.</li>
        <li><strong>Aim High:</strong> A lob shot requires you to aim the ball high over your opponent’s head. You want the ball to fly with a steep arc and drop near the back of the court, ideally in the deep corners.</li>
        <li><strong>Follow-Through:</strong> After hitting the ball, make sure to follow through with your paddle facing upward. This ensures the ball gets enough height and lands in the appropriate area of the court.</li>
        <li><strong>Depth and Placement:</strong> Depth is key. Try to position the lob deep into your opponent’s court. The deeper the ball lands, the more challenging it will be for your opponent to return it effectively.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-lg mb-6">
        Practicing these steps consistently will help you gain confidence in your lob shot and allow you to use it effectively in match situations. The goal is not just to get the ball over the net but to make it land in a difficult-to-return position.
      </p>
