    <section class="  shadow-lg rounded-lg p-6 mb-8">
      <h2 id="when-to-use" class="text-3xl font-semibold  text-pink-400 mb-4">When to Use the Lob Shot in Pickleball</h2>
      <p class="text-lg mb-6">
        The lob shot is most effective when used at the right time. Knowing when to use it is just as important as knowing how to execute it. Here are some common scenarios where the lob shot is a valuable tool:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-8 text-lg mb-6">
        <li><strong>When Your Opponent is at the Net:</strong> The lob is especially effective when your opponent is positioned at the net. By sending the ball over their head, you can force them to move back and reset, potentially neutralizing their offensive play.</li>
        <li><strong>During a Defensive Play:</strong> If you’re in a defensive situation and your opponent is pressuring you, a well-placed lob can buy you time to recover and regain control of the point.</li>
        <li><strong>To Create Angles:</strong> The lob can be used strategically to change the angles in the game. If your opponent is moving quickly towards one side of the court, a lob to the opposite corner can create an opportunity for you to capitalize.</li>
        <li><strong>To Break the Rhythm:</strong> If you find yourself in a rally where your opponent is dominating with fast shots, using a lob can break the rhythm and throw them off balance, giving you a chance to reset the point.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-lg mb-6">
        The lob should be used sparingly, as it can also be easily countered by opponents with quick reflexes. However, when executed well, it can turn the tide of a match by forcing your opponent into uncomfortable positions.
      </p>
